    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-09-08T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-09-08T14:00:00-05:00" n="149"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d149">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.51W89 U.S.S.R./115: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_BWC1"
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-09-08T15:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 8, 1934—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>235. Your 291, September 8. There is grave difficulty in fact that Congress when
                    considering Johnson bill was assured there would <pb facs="0249" n="143"
                        xml:id="pg_143"/> be no credit transactions in advance of debt agreement
                    satisfactory to the President. Nothing said to <persName corresp="#p_TAA1"
                        >Troyanovsky</persName> on any subject since conversation Wednesday
                        night<note n="64" xml:id="d149fn64">September 5.</note> and it is up to him
                    to take the next step.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MRW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moore</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
